Comment:
Our scientists are so brilliant and they already anticipated soft landing as a risk especially on the south pole. That might be one of the reasons to pick a cost-effective approach for our mission.


Now comes the brilliance of our ISRO scientists.


* The amount spent on this lunar mission was just US ~$130 million which is ~900 crore.


* This amount is just 0.13 billion compared to the actual cost of Nasa's 100 billion mission (~ 750,000 Crore).


We just used 0.12% of the actual cost of the lunar mission!


* Considering the fact that the lunar mission was a partial (or more) success, we might have just lost 180 out of 900 crores! theoretically.


* Now comes our ISRO brilliancy, even a complete mission failure will only result in loss of 900 crores, not 750,000 crores. That leaves us the option of retrying 832 times (750,000/900 -1 attempt)!


We will only stop until we get there!


Congrats ISRO - You didn't lose anything. You earn our respect! I am proud to say loudly - I am an Indian!

Title: Watch live coverage of #Chandrayaan2 landing. #ITLivestream #Vikram #NamasteMoon #ISRO
Comment: From the trajectory graph, it seems there should be some problem with some trajectory autocorrection module in the lander. Why do I think so? If you look closely at the red curve and at the blue curve, you will see a small spike the green curve makes towards north and is almost immediately brought back to the intended curve (red) by "something" (I think this "something" is some autocorrection module). Now the spike upwards or away from the red curve is caused by "something" on the moon's surface which we dont know (moon has very little atmosphere, so can't be wind, I guess.) . But the lander immediately autocorrects its path and is back on the red line. Next time that same factor hits the lander again. And this time for elongated duration of time. Why the elongated duration of time? I dont think it is because of the factor deviating the lander. I think it is a burst shot and not some continuous force. I think the trajectory autocorrection module did not start immediately this time. So the duration of time the lander was out of the red line was significantly more than the first time. Now it is commonsense to assume that once the autocorrection module starts, the lander is trying to regain its intended trajectory(the red curve) "more aggressively" than the first time. And so now you can see the lander going in the southern direction (in respect to the red curve). Maybe that module was not written correctly. So it did not stop at the right time (neither did it start at the right time). The influence of that module continued even though the effect was not present anymore. As a result it went more and more away from the red curve, finally crashing into the surface

Title: Watch live coverage of #Chandrayaan2 landing. #ITLivestream #Vikram #NamasteMoon #ISRO
Comment: Not every mission  can be measured in the binary system of success and failure. Objective of some missions are to give hope, make young minds dream, help them imagine, envision, aspire them to explore unchartered territory & now I can say with confidence to learn from failures & rise up once again. In that sense Chandrayaan 2 is a grand success. Large number of small children had assembled to watch the landing of Vikram lander. An interview randomly picked out a schoolboy & asked him "tell me honestly what do you know about the moon mission?". The boy, aged maybe 9 or 10. surprised everybody by correcting stating the date of launch, the launch vehicle GSLV MAK-III, Vikram Lander, Pragyan Rover, Multiple Orbit Maneuvers, etc. That I believe is the biggest yardstick of success when I can feel happy & satisfied that the future of Indian Science & space research is in safe hands.
